snippet.textDisplay:
This is one of the best 40k depictions I've ever seen. There is no camp here, the marines are efficient and ruthless and almost terrifying in their own right. The opponents they face are also believable, brave (or controlled) and equally calculating just outmatched.

In this final one the psychic warp threat etc is shown to be aweinspiringly ghastly, those veteran marines who put down the inquisitor seemed on edge but also did not hesitate when faced with a threat they clearly do not underestimate. That's a good way to portray the finest troops around no campy hubris here!

The camp is part of 40k to those that know it already I guess but this is how you sell it to a general audience. I really hope you keep working on this and get support to do so.

As @Splendiferation pointed out in part 4, the Astartes have their names etched into their right shoulder pad. So far we have Kohren and Monos. (Monos was the one who was reloading in Part 4 and Kohren the man with the busted eye. )
In this part we can see @2:30 Kohren's name, presumably the captain of the group.
Then again @2:36.
@2:55 we can see Kohren and another Astartes but I can't quite make out his name on his shoulder pad.
Another small detail, while Kohren is handing out the knife things at @3:09 there's the Inquisition's emblem
@3:13 we have an opportunity to see the Blasted shoulder pad guys name but I can't make it out
@3:21 MONEY SHOT Hassig! Maybe? I cant make out the first letter, its certainly -ASSIG so yeah.
@3:23 ARH motion blur is blocking my view but we CAN see his name!
@4:31 we get a chance to see this newbie's shoulder
@4:33 This Inquisitor does not have a name on his shoulder pad because Inquisition.
@4:57 HEY We got the Commander's name! HAKAM. At least I think so, I cant make out the last letter. Also the 2nd in command, that is if you can make it out through the cloud of blood.
@7:16 Sadly no name on this Salamander :((


But yeah! I hope this gets some attention and people with better monitors than me can better discern their names!

snippet.textDisplay:
I had to watch this like ten times until I realized what anyone was saying, and I am still not sure I got it right. If this thing had enough budget to go full time and a set of decent voice actors, this would be better than 99.9 percent of Hollywood stuff. This guy's talent level is phenomenal.



It also took me forever to realize that the little pillars at the foot of the enthroned skeleton statues are actually gigantic pillars the size of large buildings. The helmetless marine is standing on one. The flashes at the end are the other marines arriving in the distance. The enthroned skeleton statues must be the size of skyscrapers and the skeleton statues behind them go on and up for miles. Why would someone build such a monumental thing? What does it mean? Who built it? How long has it been sitting there?



I like that this series presents lots of ominous questions and then leaves them unanswered. It gives the universe a very lovecraftian feel.

snippet.textDisplay: Сan we finally understand that if this guy makes amazing films on his own, does not mean that he will be able to manage the huge company and budget that we all want to give him? Let's provide him possible assistance and respect his full creative freedom, and not give him the studio and the ocean of management problems. Only money doesn't solve anything at all. We should stop asking to make a full film or series from everything cool we see in trailers of Diablo IV, DOOM or this. And what the sense of having a studio if other people can't help him in making Astartes? He feel and see his creation as nobody else. Or should we entrust the creating process to endless producers, directors, deputes, and then marketers, public relations specialists, and other people who DO NOT make this film? Should the author ask someone else if they like it or not?
